<TITLE> Greece braces for power cuts in heatwave </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ATHENS, June 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Greeks should switch off their air conditioning and avoid cooking to prevent power outages during this week's heatwave, Greece's electricity utility said on Wednesday. Temperatures are expected to top 43 degrees Celsius (109.4 Fahrenheit) at the weekend and daily energy demand jumped to a year-high on Tuesday. A long, dry winter has given way to a scorchingly hot early summer that has cut water levels in hydro-electric power plants. Rising energy consumption has triggered minor power cuts in parts of the mainland and islands over recent days and fears of a nationwide electricity blackout have been growing. "There may be some damage, mainly because of cable overload, but there will be an immediate response from us when this happens," Public Power Corp. (PPC) distribution chief Dimitris Lathouris told reporters. Athenians have been told to stay out of the sun, avoid unnecessary travel and switch off energy-hungry home appliances including washing machines, boilers and air conditioners. Across the country, municipalities have set up large air-conditioned halls to provide shelter for the elderly and people with heart problems. Interior Minister Prokopis Pavlopoulos said medics, rescue teams and even the army could be called in to help. "The state apparatus is ready to deal with this heat wave," he told reporters on Wednesday. On Sunday, temperatures in Athens are expected to reach 42 degrees and 43 degrees is possible in central Greece. Temperatures reach a high of 29 degrees for the second 10-day period of June on average, and 30 in the third 10-day peri
